<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Burundi </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attempted Coup by Army Troops Collapses </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Attempted Coup by Army Troops Collapses </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Government Reportedly Hiding </H4>

<F P=102> LD2504101594 Brussels Radio Vlaanderen International in 
English 0900 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2504101594 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels Radio Vlaanderen International </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] An attempted coup has taken place in the central 
African country, Burundi. It was organized by Tutsi Army 
officers. The Burundi Army chief says the coup has failed. 
Other reports say it is still in progress. The Army is still 
controlled by the minority Tutsi people in Burundi. 
  All members of the Burundi Government have gone into hiding, 
probably in a Western embassy. This was confirmed to the BRTN 
[expansion not given] by the interim president, Ntibantunganya, 
last night. 
  Meanwhile the Army has taken action against three rebellious 
Hutu districts in Bujumbura. These are surrounded. The Tutsi 
military want to disarm militias from the majority Hutu people. 
The minister of defense has asked all inhabitants of the Hutu 
district to leave to prevent innocent victims. 
  The Belgian Embassy has asked all the Belgians in Bujumbura 
to stay inside. 
  Some Hutus formed military militias in the last few days. 
This followed reports from the Hutu party, Frodebu, that the 
Army is preparing for violence against the majority Hutu people. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

