<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IFP Charges IEC With `Incompetency' in Natal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IFP Charges IEC With `Incompetency' in Natal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2604121694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1139 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2604121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by C. Govender] </F>
  [Text] Durban April 26 SAPA -- The Inkatha Freedom Party 
[IFP] on Tuesday [26 April] accused the Independent Electoral 
Commission [IEC] of incompetency after ballot papers allegedly 
arrived at many polling booths around Durban and 
Pietermaritzburg without the party's sticker attached. 
  IFP spokesman Ed Tillett labelled it a "deep election 
crisis". "The IEC is in complete disarray. What it boils down 
to is plain incompetency," charged Mr Tillett. 
  He said areas such as Mpumalanga outside Durban, Umbumbulu 
south of the city, Warner Beach, parts of Pietermaritzburg and 
others had experienced this problem. "How can one hope to 
achieve fair election results? In vast areas (IFP supporters) 
cannot vote today." In Ulundi there was a shortage of ballot 
papers, and in many areas people did not have voter cards, said 
Mr Tillett. 
  He added top-level negotiations with the IEC were in 
progress. 
  IEC spokesman Glenn Mcdougall said late changes to the 
ballot 
paper and logistical problems, especially transport, had caused 
delays at some polling booths. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-1310 </DOCNO>
