<H3> <TI>   Seven Prisons Reportedly Complete Voting Process </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seven Prisons Reportedly Complete Voting Process </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2604130894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1244 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2604130894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by J. Rees] </F>
  [Text] Bloemfontein April 26 SAPA -- Voting in prisons 
proceeded smoothly on Tuesday [26 April] as special polling 
stations were set up for as many as 100,000 prisoners, a 
Correctional Services spokesman said. No incidents were 
reported and the atmosphere in prisons was calm, he said. 
  Independent Electoral Commission [IEC] officials set up the 
stations behind bars and guards took eligible prisoners to cast 
their votes. There was no adverse reaction from murderers, 
rapists and other prisoners denied the vote by a last-minute 
cabinet decision on Tuesday, the spokesman said. 
  Prisons Commissioner Gen Henk Bruyn this week barred the 
media from prisons in order to "keep the atmosphere as calm as 
possible". 
  Officials on Tuesday had no clear idea of how many of the 
country's 115,000 prisoners would vote, but estimated the figure 
could come close to 100,000. 
  In the Orange Free State and Northern Cape seven prisons had 
completed voting by noon on Tuesday, a spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

