<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Klerk Encourages All Citizens To Vote </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    De Klerk Encourages All Citizens To Vote </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2604101394 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0952 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2604101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by N. Patterton] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria April 26 SAPA -- President F W de Klerk on 
Tuesday encouraged people to vote, saying polling stations were 
perhaps the safest places in South Africa with "tremendous" 
safety measures taken by security forces. He promised a 
clampdown by government on those responsible for the spate of 
bombings linked to the elections. 
  He was speaking at the Karmel old age home in Pretoria where 
he had taken his mother, Mrs Corrie de Klerk, aged 89, to cast 
her special vote. 
  Mr de Klerk told journalists that the government and the new 
government of national unity would act sternly against those 
responsible for the bombings, thought to be a "lunatic fringe on 
the right". 
  He said no conclusions could be reached from voting patterns 
so far, adding that he expected a high average percentage. He 
was glad that technical hitches experienced at some polling 
stations on Tuesday morning had been ironed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

