<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conservative Party Members Defect to Freedom Front </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Conservative Party Members Defect to Freedom Front </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2504194894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1819 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2504194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by E. van Wyk] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria April 25 SAPA -- Eight Conservative Party 
[CP] city councillors from Pretoria have joined the Freedom 
Front [FF], FF spokesman Stephan Maninger said on Monday. This 
was part of the "overwhelming support" the FF and its leader 
General Constand Viljoen were attracting countrywide from CP and 
National Party [NP] members, he said in a statement. 
  Over the weekend two senior CP MPs, Tom Langley and Dries 
Bruwer, defected to the FF. Mr Bruwer is also president of the 
Transvaal Agricultural Union. Last week 11 CP-controlled town 
councils pledged support for Gen Viljoen. 
  In a seperate statement Mr Maninger dismissed as "devoid of 
all truth" rumours that the FF was considering forming a 
coalition with the NP. The policies of the FF and the NP were 
"world's apart" and such a coalition could never happen because 
the NP was already in a de facto alliance with the African 
National Congress, he said. 
  The rumours had originated from the rightwing broadcaster 
Radio Pretoria, Mr Maninger said. Critising the radio station, 
Mr Maninger said Radio Pretoria had in the past broadcast the 
opinions of individuals as facts. He accused the radio station 
of biased reporting, saying that the broadcaster did not "even 
tolerate differing views anymore". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

