<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IEC Orders Urgent Printing of 5.4 Million Ballots </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IEC Orders Urgent Printing of 5.4 Million Ballots </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Army Helps Print Ballots </H4>

<F P=102> MB2804082294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 0800 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2804082294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria April 28 SAPA -- The Army worked through 
the night printing extra ballot papers, then rushed them to Air 
Force planes before dawn for delivery to areas around the 
country where thousands were waiting to cast their votes. 
  A spokesman for the SA [South African] National Defence 
Force 
said, after a request by the Independent Electoral Commission 
[IEC] on Wednesday afternoon [27 April] , the Army's 1 Military 
Printing Regiment had 375,000 ballot papers printed by 6AM on 
Thursday. It hoped to have another batch of 300,000 ready for 
dispatch by 9.30AM. 
  The operation had started at 6PM on Wednesday, and by 3.30AM 
the first batch of 210,000 had been delivered to Waterkloof Air 
Force Base for dispatch to areas designated by the IEC. A 
second batch of 165,000 had been delivered by 6AM, and was sent 
by the IEC to Ulundi. 

</TEXT>

