<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-082-S </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Problems at Regional Polling Stations Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Problems at Regional Polling Stations Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Vehicle Transporting Ballots Hijacked </H4>

<F P=102> MB2704105294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1010 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2704105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Solly Liefman] </F>
  [Text] Johannesburg April 27 SAPA -- An Independent 
Electoral Commission [IEC] vehicle transporting ballot papers to 
a polling station in Eldorado Park, southwest of Johannesburg, 
was reportedly hijacked on Wednesday [27 April]. Police could 
not comment immediately. It is understood the vehicle was 
hijacked by four men on its way to a polling station at a school 
in the area. 
  The vehicle was later recovered by police, with only four 
boxes of ballot papers. The rest of the papers were missing. 
The IEC men in the vehicle were unhurt. Two men were 
reportedly arrested by police, but this could also not be 
confirmed. IEC officials, escorted by police, went to collect 
more ballot papers. 
  By just before noon on Wednesday, a 3km queue had developed 
at the polling station. Also in the queue were scores of voters 
from nearby squatter settlements and from Soweto and Pimville 
townships, outside Eldorado Park. 
  Voting at the polling station in the coloured area began 
just 
after 7AM. 

</TEXT>

