<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Klerk Responds to Mandela's Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    De Klerk Responds to Mandela's Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2804114894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1131 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2804114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town April 28 SAPA -- The allegation by African 
National Congress President Nelson Mandela that problems had 
only occured at polling stations where blacks were voting was 
extremely serious and should be backed up by facts, State 
President F W de Klerk said on Thursday [28 April] afternoon. 
"It is a very serious allegation and he will have to back it up 
with facts. As far as I know, he has not provided one single 
fact for that allegation," he said at a press conference at the 
National Party [NP] offices in Cape Town. 
  Mr de Klerk was reacting to an earlier allegation of 
"sabotage" made by Mr Mandela in an interview with SABC [South 
African Broadcasting Corporation] television. "The NP has 
complained that the overwhelming majority of Independent 
Electoral Commission [IEC] officials at grassroots and polling 
station official level have been breaking the rules and have not 
been impartial. We have much to complain about. The IEC is 
sufficiently representative -- and on certain levels loaded in 
favour of the ANC -- of all political parties. I have travelled 
far and wide and have not heard -- apart from specific polling 
stations -- any accusations of malpractice which has the type of 
basis of Mr Mandela's statement. I'm shocked at it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

