<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Airport Bombing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Airport Bombing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2704064594 Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network in English 0545 
GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2704064594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SABC TV 1 Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with KwaZulu Chief Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi </F>
by correspondent Caro Kriel and unidentified correspondent at 
Umlazi, Durban -- live] 
  [Excerpts] [Kriel] We're back in Umlazi where IFP [Inkatha 
Freedom Party] leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi is still standing by 
for an interview. Mr. Buthelezi, the first thing we'd like to 
know from you is comment. We believe that a bomb has exploded 
at Jan Smuts Airport. We have no further details. It's 
absolutely not clear what has happened. What is your comment? 
  [Buthelezi] Well, I'm distressed by it, because I think that 
today should be the dawn of a new South Africa, but I mean, if 
the new South Africa is born, you know, in the midst of bombings 
of the kind that we've seen in the last few days, then that 
doesn't augur well for the future peace and prosperity of this 
country, and therefore I'm extremely distressed that it's 
on-going, even now. [passage omitted] 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Dr. Buthelezi, what would your 
comment be on the reports that a bomb has exploded at Jan Smuts? 
  [Buthelezi] I'm very distressed by it, because I think that 
it is very tragic that the new South Africa should be born 
amidst the bomb blasts that we have seen in the last few days, 
and I'm distressed because I believe that that doesn't augur 
well for the future of this country, because quite clearly those 
who are doing so mean to destabilize the country, and once the 
country is destabilized, of course, we are not going to get 
prosperity and peace, which are the major objectives, and have 
been major objectives of our struggle. 
  [Correspondent] Do you think the police are doing more to 
arrest the perpetrators of this latest violence? 
  [Buthelezi] It's very difficult to judge them because I 
think 
that, very unwisely, Mr. de Klerk declared a state of emergency 
in this region, and therefore I think the police as such, and 
all the security forces, are spread very thinly on top, because 
some of them are here in Natal and KwaZulu, whereas, in fact, 
because of the political problems they have really abandoned 
their ordinary policing work to concentrate on the political 
problems, and the political violence, and therefore I wouldn't 
be judgmental and say that they are not doing enough, because 
I'm a realist. I realize that, you know, human beings, such a 
number of human beings can do just so much, and no more. 
  [Correspondent] In your opinion, who is responsible for 
this? 
  [Buthelezi] Well, I really would be a prophet to say so. I 
wish I knew who did it, in fact. Just like you, I won't know 
that until one person is arrested, indicating from what group he 
comes. I've no idea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-1431 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr082_cs94024" </HT>


