<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   British Observer Says `No Interference' in Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    British Observer Says `No Interference' in Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2804082794 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 0725 GMT 28 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2804082794 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Former Labour leader Neil Kinnock today said there 
had been no attempt by any of the parties in South Africa's 
general election to interfere "in any malign way" with voting 
procedures. 
  Asked if there had been any fiddling Mr. Kinnock, who is 
leading some 20 British parliamentarians acting as monitors and 
observers, said: "We have seen no evidence. Any problems have 
been inadvertent problems of distance or supply or simply 
inexperience. There has been no attempt by any of the parties 
to interfere in any malign way with voting procedures." 
  Mr. Kinnock, whose group has visited 19 polling stations 
over 
several hundred square miles, told BBC Radio 4's Today programme 
that an extension of voting to midnight tonight would be very 
sensible. 

</TEXT>

