<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IFP To Complain About U.S. Election Minitor's Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IFP To Complain About U.S. Election Minitor's Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB2704203794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2003 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2704203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by D. Issacson] </F>
  [Text] Durban April 27 SAPA -- The Inkatha Freedom Party 
[IFP] intends to complain to American President Bill Clinton 
about remarks made by a U.S. election monitor on South African 
television on Wednesday [27 April] night. IFP spokesman Ed 
Tillet said the remarks were partisan and uninformed. 
  He said U.S. monitor Nellie Bailey referred to IFP President 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi as having "colluded with the racist regime" 
and was also critical of the party's late entry into the 
elections. 
  "We do not expect foreign observers to interfere in South 
Africa's domestic affairs or deliver hostile political judgments 
against any political party or leader during the transition to 
democracy," Mr Tillet said in a statement. 
  The IFP would ask the U.S. ambassador to forward the 
complaint to Mr Clinton. 

</TEXT>

